{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658274"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20725"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20725"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0,0.8,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96797"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13601"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79412"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10956"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11791"},{"type":"tags","id":"12603"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96797"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA lung biopsy shows extensive collagen deposition with scattered inflammatory cells including macrophages and lymphocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological outcome of chronic inflammation in this tissue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Granuloma formation","Acute suppurative inflammation","Fibrosis with tissue remodelling","Complete resolution of inflammation","Amyloid deposition"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe biopsy findings demonstrate \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrosis with tissue remodelling\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a common outcome of chronic inflammation. This is characterised by excessive deposition of collagen and other extracellular matrix components, leading to scarring and distortion of normal tissue architecture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranuloma formation\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern shows aggregates of epithelioid macrophages and giant cells, which are not described in the biopsy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute suppurative inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves neutrophil-rich exudates and pus formation, typical of acute rather than chronic inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete resolution of inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - The presence of ongoing inflammation and collagen deposition indicates this has not resolved\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloid deposition\u003C/strong\u003E - This involves abnormal protein deposition rather than the collagen deposition seen here\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic inflammation can have several outcomes: resolution (rare without removing the stimulus), fibrosis (as in this case), continued tissue destruction, or a combination of ongoing inflammation with attempts at repair.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic inflammation can lead to four main outcomes: scarring, progressive tissue destruction, persistent injury with ongoing inflammation, or resolution.","Fibrosis is a common outcome of chronic inflammation where excessive collagen deposition leads to scar formation and potential organ dysfunction.","Persistent inflammation can cause progressive tissue destruction through the release of reactive oxygen species and proteolytic enzymes from inflammatory cells."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 101"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79412"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20725"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79412"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:14:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:15:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13601"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96797"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10956"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Chronic inflammation","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:14:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11791"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Morphologic patte